# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: playwright-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] The term **asynchronous** refers to two or more objects or events that do not exist or happen at the same time, that is, they are **not** synchronous.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] When multiple related things happen without any being dependent on the completion of previous happenings, they are asynchronous.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] In computing, the word "asynchronous" is used in two major contexts, as explained below.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] Asynchronous communication is a method of exchanging messages in which the sending, receiving, and processing of each message is not dependent on the sending, receipt, or processing of other messages.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] In asynchronous communication, each party receives and processes messages when convenient or possible to do so, rather than doing so immediately upon receipt.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] Additionally, messages may be sent without waiting for acknowledgement, with the understanding that if a problem occurs, the recipient will request corrections or otherwise handle the situation.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] Email is a type of asynchronous human communication.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] The recipient reads the email and responds to it (or not) at their convenience, not necessarily right away.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] All parties can continue to send and receive messages at any time.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] Emails don't have to be scheduled in a particular sequence.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] In asynchronous software, making a request, such as to a server, does not block other processes while waiting for the response.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] The software can continue performing other tasks.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] For example, in promise-based APIs, `Promise` objects are created for long operations.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] After the operation is complete, the promise is handled.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] With promises, the software doesn't have to wait for the operation to finish.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] Asynchronous software design expands upon the concept by building code that allows a program to ask that a task be performed alongside the original task (or tasks), without stopping to wait for the task to complete.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] When the secondary task is completed, the original task is notified using an agreed-upon mechanism so that it knows the work is done, and that the result, if any, is available.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] There are a number of programming techniques for implementing asynchronous software.
[src:playwright-automation/asynchronous] See the article Asynchronous JavaScript for an introduction to them.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] A **headless browser** is a web browser without a graphical user interface.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] Headless browsers provide automated control of a web page in an environment similar to popular web browsers, but they are executed via a command-line interface or using network communication.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] They are particularly useful for testing web pages as they are able to render and understand HTML the same way a browser would, including styling elements such as page layout, color, font selection and execution of JavaScript and Ajax which are usually not available when using other testing methods.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] Since version 59 of Google Chrome and version 56 of Firefox, there is native support for remote control of the browser.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] This made earlier efforts obsolete, notably PhantomJS.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] Headless browsers are also useful for web scraping.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] Google stated in 2009 that using a headless browser could help their search engine index content from websites that use Ajax.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] However, a study of browser traffic in 2018 found no preference by malicious actors for headless browsers.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] There is no indication that headless browsers are used more frequently than non-headless browsers for malicious purposes, like DDoS attacks, SQL injections or cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] As several major browsers natively support headless mode through APIs, some software exists to perform browser automation through a unified interface.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] Some test automation software and frameworks include headless browsers as part of their testing apparati.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] Another approach is to use software that provides browser APIs.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] For example, Deno provides browser APIs as part of its design.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] For Node.js, jsdom is the most complete provider.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] While most are able to support common browser features (HTML parsing, cookies, XHR, some JavaScript, etc.), they do not render the DOM and have limited support for DOM events.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] They usually perform faster than full browsers, but are unable to correctly interpret many popular websites.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] Another is HtmlUnit, a headless browser written in Java.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] HtmlUnit uses the Rhino engine to provide JavaScript and Ajax support as well as partial rendering capability.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] These are various software that provide headless browser APIs.
[src:playwright-automation/headless-browser] An earlier effort (2008) was envjs from John Resig, which was a simulated browser environment written in JavaScript for the Rhino engine.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] Playwright Test is an end-to-end test framework for modern web apps.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] It bundles test runner, assertions, isolation, parallelization and rich tooling.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] Playwright supports Chromium, WebKit and Firefox on Windows, Linux and macOS, locally or in CI, headless or headed, with native mobile emulation for Chrome (Android) and Mobile Safari.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] Get started by installing Playwright using one of the following methods.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] The command below either initializes a new project or adds Playwright to an existing one.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] You can re-run the command later; it does not overwrite existing tests.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] You can also create and run tests with the VS Code Extension.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] Playwright downloads required browser binaries and creates the scaffold below.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] The playwright.config centralizes configuration: target browsers, timeouts, retries, projects, reporters and more.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] In existing projects dependencies are added to your current `package.json`.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] `tests/` contains a minimal starter test.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] By default tests run headless in parallel across Chromium, Firefox and WebKit (configurable in playwright.config).
[src:playwright-automation/intro] Output and aggregated results display in the terminal.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] See Running Tests for details on filtering, headed mode, sharding and retries.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] After a test run, the HTML Reporter provides a dashboard filterable by the browser, passed, failed, skipped, flaky and more.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] Click a test to inspect errors, attachments and steps.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] It auto-opens only when failures occur; open manually with the command below.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] Run tests with UI Mode for watch mode, live step view, time travel debugging and more.
[src:playwright-automation/intro] See the detailed guide on UI Mode for watch filters, step details and trace integration.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Playwright is a framework for web automation and testing.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] It drives Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit with a single API — in your tests, in your scripts, and as a tool for AI agents.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Playwright Test is a full-featured test runner built for end-to-end testing.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] It runs tests across Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit with full browser isolation, auto-waiting, and web-first assertions.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Tests run in parallel across all configured browsers, in headless mode by default.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Each test gets a fresh browser context — full isolation with near-zero overhead.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Playwright CLI is a command-line interface for browser automation designed for coding agents.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] It's more token-efficient than MCP — commands avoid loading large tool schemas and accessibility trees into the model context.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Use `playwright-cli show` to open a visual dashboard with live screencast previews of all running browser sessions.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Click any session to zoom in and take remote control.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] The Playwright MCP server gives AI agents full browser control through the Model Context Protocol.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Agents interact with pages using structured accessibility snapshots — no vision models or screenshots required.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] It uses element refs like `e5` and `e10` to click, type, and interact — deterministically and without visual ambiguity.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Tools cover navigation, form filling, screenshots, network mocking, storage management, and more.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Use `playwright` as a library for browser automation scripts — web scraping, PDF generation, screenshot capture, and any workflow that needs programmatic browser control without a test runner.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] The Playwright VS Code extension brings test running, debugging, and code generation directly into your editor.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Headless and headed execution on all platforms.
[src:playwright-automation/microsoft-playwright] Playwright is also available for Python, .NET, and Java.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:playwright-automation/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] A **web browser**, often abbreviated as **browser**, is an application for accessing websites.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] When a user requests a web page from a particular website, the browser retrieves its files from a web server and then displays the page on the user's screen.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Browsers can also display content stored locally on the user's device.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Browsers are used on a range of devices, including desktops, laptops, tablets, smartphones, smartwatches, smart televisions and consoles.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] As of 2026, the most used browsers worldwide are Google Chrome (~69% market share), Safari (~16%), Edge (~5%), Firefox (~2%), Samsung Browser (~2%), and Opera (~2%).
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] As of 2023, an estimated 5.4 billion people had used a browser.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The purpose of a web browser is to fetch content and display it on the user's device.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] This process begins when the user inputs a Uniform Resource Locator (URL), such as *`https://en.wikipedia.org/`*, into the browser's address bar.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Virtually all URLs on the Web start with either *`http:`* or *`https:`* which means they are retrieved with the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] For secure mode (HTTPS), the connection between the browser and web server is encrypted, providing a secure and private data transfer.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] For this reason, a web browser is often referred to as an HTTP client or a user agent.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Requisite materials, including text, style sheets, images, and other types of multimedia, are downloaded from the server.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Once the materials have been downloaded, the web browser's engine (also known as a layout engine or rendering engine) is responsible for converting those resources into an interactive visual representation of the page on the user's device.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Modern web browsers also contain separate JavaScript engines which enable more complex interactive applications inside the browser.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] A web browser that does not render a graphical user interface is known as a headless browser.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Web pages usually contain hyperlinks to other pages and resources.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Each link contains a URL, and when it is clicked or tapped, the browser navigates to the new resource.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Most browsers use an internal cache of web page resources to improve loading times for subsequent visits to the same page.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The cache can store many items, such as large images, so they do not need to be downloaded from the server again.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Cached items are usually only stored for as long as the web server stipulates in its HTTP response messages.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] A web browser is not the same thing as a search engine, though the two are often confused.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] A search engine is a website that provides links to other websites and allows users to search for specific resources using a textual query.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] However, web browsers are often used to access search engines, and most modern browsers allow users to access a default search engine directly by typing a query into the address bar.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The first web browser, called WorldWideWeb, was created in 1990 by Sir Tim Berners-Lee.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] He then recruited Nicola Pellow to write the Line Mode Browser, which displayed web pages on dumb terminals.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The Mosaic web browser was released in April 1993, and was later credited as the first web browser to find mainstream popularity.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Its innovative graphical user interface made the World Wide Web easy to navigate and thus more accessible to the average person.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] This, in turn, sparked the Internet boom of the 1990s, when the Web grew at a very rapid rate.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released the Mosaic-influenced Netscape Navigator in 1994.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Navigator quickly became the most popular browser.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Within a few years, Microsoft gained a dominant position in the browser market for two reasons: it bundled Internet Explorer with its popular Windows operating system and did so as freeware with no restrictions on usage.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The market share of Internet Explorer peaked at over 95% in the early 2000s.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] In 1998, Netscape launched what would become the Mozilla Foundation to create a new browser using the open-source software model.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] This work evolved into the Firefox browser, first released by Mozilla in 2004.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Firefox's market share peaked at 32% in 2010.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Apple released its Safari browser in 2003; it remains the dominant browser on Apple devices, though it did not become popular elsewhere.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, which steadily took market share from Internet Explorer and became the most popular browser in 2012.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Chrome has remained dominant ever since.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] In 2015, Microsoft replaced Internet Explorer with Edge [Legacy] for the Windows 10 release.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] In 2020, this legacy version was replaced by a new Chromium-based version of Edge.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Since the early 2000s, browsers have greatly expanded their HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and multimedia capabilities.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] One reason has been to enable more sophisticated websites, such as web apps.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Another factor is the significant increase of broadband connectivity in many parts of the world, enabling people to access data-intensive content, such as streaming HD video on YouTube, that was not possible during the era of dial-up modems.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Starting in the mid-2020s, browsers with integrated artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities, known as AI browsers, have become increasingly common.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] This includes both new entrants to the browser market, such as Perplexity Comet and ChatGPT Atlas, and established browsers that added AI features, such as Chrome with the Gemini chatbot and Edge with the Copilot chatbot.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The most popular browsers share many features.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] They automatically log users' browsing history, unless the users turn off their browsing history or use the non-logging private mode.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] They also allow users to set bookmarks, customize the browser with extensions, and manage their downloads and passwords.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Some provide a sync service and web accessibility features.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] While mobile browsers have similar UI features as desktop versions, the limitations of the often-smaller touch screens require mobile UIs to be simpler.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The difference is significant for users accustomed to keyboard shortcuts.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Responsive web design is used to create websites that offer a consistent experience across the desktop and mobile versions of the website and across varying screen sizes.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The most popular desktop browsers also have sophisticated web development tools.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Access to some web content — particularly streaming services like Netflix, Disney+, and Spotify — is restricted by Digital Rights Management (DRM) software.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] A web browser is able to access DRM-restricted content through the use of a Content Decryption Module (CDM) such as Widevine.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] As of 2020, the CDMs used by dominant web browsers require browser providers to pay costly license fees, making it unfeasible for most independent open-source browsers to offer access to DRM-restricted content.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Google Chrome has been the dominant browser worldwide since the mid-2010s and currently has a 69% global market share on all devices.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] The other two browsers in the top four are made from different codebases.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Safari, based on Apple's WebKit code, is the second most popular web browser and is dominant on Apple devices, resulting in a 16% global share.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Firefox, in fourth place, with about 2% market share, is based on Mozilla's code.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Both of these codebases are open-source, so a number of small niche browsers are also made from them.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Prior to late 2016, the majority of web traffic came from desktop computers.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] However, since then, mobile devices (smartphones) have represented the majority of web traffic.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] As of February 2025, mobile devices represent a 62% share of Internet traffic, followed by desktop at 36% and tablet at 2%.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Web browsers are popular targets for hackers, who exploit security holes to steal information, destroy files, and partake in other malicious activities.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Browser vendors regularly patch these security holes, so users are strongly encouraged to keep their browser software updated.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Other protection measures are antivirus software and being aware of scams.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] During the course of browsing, cookies received from various websites are stored by the browser.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Some of them contain login credentials or site preferences.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] However, others are used for tracking user behavior over long periods of time, so browsers typically provide a section in the menu for deleting cookies.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Some browsers have more proactive protection against cookies and trackers that limit their functionality and ability to track user behaviour.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Finer-grained management of cookies usually requires a browser extension.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Telemetry data is collected by most popular web browsers, which can usually be opted out of by the user.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] A study from 2020 portrays that there are two tiers of browsers in terms of privacy: the privacy-focused ones (Brave, DuckDuckGo, LibreWolf, Tor,Mullvad, Helium and Firefox-Focus) perform better than popular ones (Chrome, Firefox, and Safari) and recommend the first ones.
[src:playwright-automation/web-browser] Blocking fingerprinting, cookies, tracking scripts, ads, etc. seems to explain that difference.
